keywords = {contrast enhancement, digital number, histogram equalisation, histogram matching, histogram modification, image comparison, visual observation},
abstract = {Summary Contrast enhancement, sometimes called radiometric enhancement or histogram modification, is the most basic but also the most effective technique to optimise the image contrast and brightness for visualisation or to highlight information in particular digital number (DN) ranges. Logarithmic and exponential functions are inverse operations of one another. For contrast enhancement, the two functions modify the image histograms in opposite ways. Histogram equalisation (HE) transforms an input image to an output image with a uniform (equalised) histogram. Histogram matching (HM) is particularly useful for image comparison and differencing. If the two images in question are modified to have similar histograms, the comparison will be on a fair basis. Clipping is often given as a percentage of the total number of pixels in an image. The general purpose of contrast enhancement is to optimise visualisation. Visual observation is always the most effective way to judge image quality.}
}
