abstract = {Summary In remote sensing applications, geometric operations are mainly used for the co-registration of images of the same scene acquired by different sensor systems or at different times or from different positions, and for rectifying an image to fit a particular coordinate system (geocoding). The rubber sheet warping, based on a polynomial deformation model, is the most important and commonly used geometric transformation for remotely sensed image data. A deformation model can be derived by fitting a polynomial function to ground control point (GCP) locations. GCP can be selected manually, semi-automatically or automatically. With rapid development of computer vision technology, GCP selection and image co-registration has been largely automated between images of similar illumination condition and spectral/spatial property. However, the manual and semi-automatic GCP selection is still needed for co-registration between images from different sources and with very different spectral property and spatial characteristics, and for co-registration between images and maps.}
